VA rare treat by Nihal
p3
sVnews
p4
VRarely do we come across well-trained Carnatic musicians among film music composers. Nihal, formerly known as K.V. Srinivas, is an exception. He is a busy playback singer and film music composer. He gave a  Carnatic vocal recital at the Thyagaraya Gana Sabha organised by  Sangeetha Ksheera Sagaram last week. Srinivas is a gold medallist postgraduate in Music from Telugu University&#8217;s first batch. He has given concerts abroad under the aegis of ICCR.Later, he became a part of the movie world and changed his name to Nihal. His first guru was the late Carnatic musician Tampella Suryanarayana and later he learnt from Nookala Chinna Satyanarayana for a while.However, it was his hard work that stood by him and brought him where he is today. He is blessed with a melodious voice with enviable compass.He revealed  himself asEkalavya shishyaof the melody of Maharajapuram Santanam, the pace of T.N. Seshagopalan,ragaalapanaof K.V. Narayanaswamy andswaraprastharaof T.V. Sankara Narayanan. All these traits of thegreat men could be seen in his rare concert here.As his reputation as playback singer walked before him, the audience turned out in large numbers He concluded it with Maharajapuram Santanam&#8217;s tillana that he redesigned in theragamalikaformat. Accompanied by R. Dinakar on the violin, V. Kaliprasad on the mridangam and K. Shyamkumar on Kanjira, Nihal gave a traditional opening to his concert with a Nata raga composition,Ninne Bhajana, of Thyagaraja, adding to it an expansive and exercisingRama Ramaof Patnam was his chosenkritiin which thenerevalandswaraprastharamade for beautiful listening.  Thetani avartanamby the percussionists elevated the total impact of the number.
